{"title_page": "Anil Sharma (Uttar Pradesh politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix        =\n | name                    =  Anil Sharma<br>\u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e\n | honorific-suffix        =\n | image                   = \n | alt                     =\n | caption                 = \n| office                  = Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden<br>[[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]\n | term_start              = 21 August 2019\n | term_end                = \n | predecessor             = \n| 1blankname = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata = [[Yogi Adityanath]]\n | successor               = \n | constituency1            = [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur]], [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]]\n| constituency3            = [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]], [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]]\n | office1                  = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]], [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]]\n | term_start1              = 11 March 2017\n | term_end1                = \n | predecessor1             = [[Mukesh Sharma]]\n | successor1               = \n| term_start2              = May 2007\n | term_end2              = March 2012\n | predecessor2             = \n | successor2              = [[Banshi Singh]]\n| term_start3              = February 2002\n | term_end3              = May 2007\n | predecessor3             = Harpal Singh\n | successor3              = \n | birth_date              = {{Birth date and  age|df=yes|1963|06|26}}\n | birth_place            =Surjawali, [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref name=Profile/>\n | restingplace            =\n | restingplacecoordinates =\n | birthname               =\n | parents                 =  Vijay Kumar Sharma<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\"/>\n | nationality             = Indian\n | party                   = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| spouse                  ={{marriage|Moirta Sharma|1987}}\n | partner                 =\n | relations               =\n | children                = 2\n | residence               = \n | alma_mater              = [[Higher Secondary School Certificate|Intermediate]]\n | occupation              = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]]\n | profession              = Politician<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\"/>\n}}\n'''Anil Sharma''' is an [[India]]n politician and a member of 17th Legislative Assembly of [[Uttar Pradesh]] of [[India]]. He represents the [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)]] in [[Bulandshahr district]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and is a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\">{{cite news|title=Candidate affidavit|publisher= my neta.info|url=http://www.myneta.info/uttarpradesh2017/candidate.php?candidate_id=231|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Currently he is serving as Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden in [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=LH>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livehindustan.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandsehar/story-shikarpur-mla-anil-sharma-becomes-minister-of-state-wave-of-happiness-in-the-district-2700878.html|title=\u0936\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0930\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u091c\u093f\u0932\u0947 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0916\u0941\u0936\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0932\u0939\u0930|date=21 August 2019|work=Live Hindustan|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharad Ashthana|first=|url=https://www.patrika.com/bulandshahr-news/anil-sharma-bjp-mla-bulandshahr-shikarpur-biography-in-hindi-4998479/|title=\u092e\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u0915\u0930\u0940\u092c\u0940 \u0930\u0939 \u091a\u0941\u0915\u0947 \u0907\u0938 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0915\u094b \u092f\u094b\u0917\u0940 \u0938\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0928\u093e\u092f\u093e \u0917\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u092f\u0939 \u092e\u0939\u0924\u094d\u200d\u0935\u092a\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0923 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093e\u0917 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0917\u093e|date=24 August 2019|work=Patrika|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandshahr-anil-sharma-said-there-will-be-emphasis-on-development-district-will-get-the-benefit-of-every-scheme-19506372.html|title=Yogi Cabinet Expansion: \u0935\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0938 \u092a\u0930 \u0939\u094b\u0917\u093e \u091c\u094b\u0930, \u091c\u093f\u0932\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0938\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u094b \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0939\u0930 \u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0932\u093e\u092d : \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e|date=21 August 2019|work=Jagran|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandshahr-minister-of-state-anil-sharma-welcomed-on-arrival-in-the-city-19527573.html|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0936\u0939\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092a\u0939\u0941\u0902\u091a\u0928\u0947 \u092a\u0930 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0917\u0924|date=29 August 2019|work=Jagran|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSharma was born 26 June 1963 in Surjawali village [[Bulandshahr district]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] to his father Vijay Kumar Sharma. In 1987, he married with Moirta Sharma, they have one son and one daughter. He had completed [[Higher Secondary School Certificate|Intermediate]] education from [[Board of High School and Intermediate Education Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=http://www.upvidhansabhaproceedings.gov.in/member?memberId=20006|work=official website of Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh|title=Member Profile|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Political career==\nSharma started his journey in politics from the [[village head]] (Pradhan). In 1989, Anil Sharma was elected unopposed village head of the ancestral village Surjawali for the first time. After that, he became the village head for the second consecutive time.<ref name=LH/>\n\nIn 2002, Anil Sharma was elected [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja Assembly]] seat on [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] ticket for the first time. Then for the second consecutive time in 2007, Anil Sharma became [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]]. In the year 2012, [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]] seat was secured. He contested on the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] ticket from [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur Assembly]] seat but lost to [[Samajwadi Party|SP]]'s [[Mukesh Sharma]]. In the year 2017, he was elected MLA from [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur Assembly]] seat as a member of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=LH/>\n==Post helds==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! # !! From !! To !! Position !! Comments\n|-\n| 1 ||February 2002 || May 2007|| Member, [[14th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref name=\" 2002 Election Results  \">{{cite news|title= 2002 Election Results|publisher=[[Election Commission of India]] website|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_2002/Stat_rep_UP_2002.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2 ||May 2007 || March 2012 || Member, [[15th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref name=\" 2007 Election Results  \">{{cite news|title= 2007 Election Results|publisher=[[Election Commission of India]] website|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_2007/StatReport_AS_2007_UTTAR_PRADESH.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3 ||March 2017 || Incumbent || Member, [[17th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eci.nic.in/eci_main/archiveofge2017/UP/10.Detailed%20Results.pdf|title=Uttar Pradesh 2017 Result|website=Election Commission of India|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4 ||August 2019 || Incumbent || Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden in [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|India|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Anil}}\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix        =\n | name                    =  Anil Sharma<br>\u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e\n | honorific-suffix        =\n | image                   = \n | alt                     =\n | caption                 = \n| office                  = Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden<br>[[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]\n | term_start              = 21 August 2019\n | term_end                = \n | predecessor             = \n| 1blankname = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata = [[Yogi Adityanath]]\n | successor               = \n | constituency1            = [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur]], [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]]\n| constituency3            = [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]], [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]]\n | office1                  = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]], [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]]\n | term_start1              = 11 March 2017\n | term_end1                = \n | predecessor1             = [[Mukesh Sharma]]\n | successor1               = \n| term_start2              = May 2007\n | term_end2              = March 2012\n | predecessor2             = \n | successor2              = [[Banshi Singh]]\n| term_start3              = February 2002\n | term_end3              = May 2007\n | predecessor3             = Harpal Singh\n | successor3              = \n | birth_date              = {{Birth date and  age|df=yes|1963|06|26}}\n | birth_place            =Surjawali, [[Bulandshahr district|Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref name=Profile/>\n | restingplace            =\n | restingplacecoordinates =\n | birthname               =\n | parents                 =  Vijay Kumar Sharma<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\"/>\n | nationality             = Indian\n | party                   = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| spouse                  ={{marriage|Moirta Sharma|1987}}\n | partner                 =\n | relations               =\n | children                = 2\n | residence               = \n | alma_mater              = [[Higher Secondary School Certificate|Intermediate]]\n | occupation              = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]]\n | profession              = Politician<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\"/>\n}}\n'''Anil Sharma''' is an [[India]]n politician and a member of 17th Legislative Assembly of [[Uttar Pradesh]] of [[India]]. He represents the [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)]] in [[Bulandshahr district]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and is a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=\"Candidate affidavit\">{{cite news|title=Candidate affidavit|publisher= my neta.info|url=http://www.myneta.info/uttarpradesh2017/candidate.php?candidate_id=231|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Currently he is serving as Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden in [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=LH>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.livehindustan.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandsehar/story-shikarpur-mla-anil-sharma-becomes-minister-of-state-wave-of-happiness-in-the-district-2700878.html|title=\u0936\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0930\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u091c\u093f\u0932\u0947 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0916\u0941\u0936\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0932\u0939\u0930|date=21 August 2019|work=Live Hindustan|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharad Ashthana|first=|url=https://www.patrika.com/bulandshahr-news/anil-sharma-bjp-mla-bulandshahr-shikarpur-biography-in-hindi-4998479/|title=\u092e\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u0915\u0930\u0940\u092c\u0940 \u0930\u0939 \u091a\u0941\u0915\u0947 \u0907\u0938 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0915\u094b \u092f\u094b\u0917\u0940 \u0938\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0928\u093e\u092f\u093e \u0917\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940, \u092f\u0939 \u092e\u0939\u0924\u094d\u200d\u0935\u092a\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0923 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093e\u0917 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0917\u093e|date=24 August 2019|work=Patrika|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandshahr-anil-sharma-said-there-will-be-emphasis-on-development-district-will-get-the-benefit-of-every-scheme-19506372.html|title=Yogi Cabinet Expansion: \u0935\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0938 \u092a\u0930 \u0939\u094b\u0917\u093e \u091c\u094b\u0930, \u091c\u093f\u0932\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0938\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u094b \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0939\u0930 \u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0932\u093e\u092d : \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e|date=21 August 2019|work=Jagran|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.jagran.com/uttar-pradesh/bulandshahr-minister-of-state-anil-sharma-welcomed-on-arrival-in-the-city-19527573.html|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0905\u0928\u093f\u0932 \u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0915\u093e \u0936\u0939\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092a\u0939\u0941\u0902\u091a\u0928\u0947 \u092a\u0930 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0917\u0924|date=29 August 2019|work=Jagran|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live|language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSharma was born 26 June 1963 in Surjawali village [[Bulandshahr district]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] to his father Vijay Kumar Sharma. In 1987, he married with Moirta Sharma, they have one son and one daughter. He had completed [[Higher Secondary School Certificate|Intermediate]] education from [[Board of High School and Intermediate Education Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=http://www.upvidhansabhaproceedings.gov.in/member?memberId=20006|work=official website of Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh|title=Member Profile|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Political career==\nSharma started his journey in politics from the [[village head]] (Pradhan). In 1989, Anil Sharma was elected unopposed village head of the ancestral village Surjawali for the first time. After that, he became the village head for the second consecutive time.<ref name=LH/>\n\nIn 2002, Anil Sharma was elected [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja Assembly]] seat on [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] ticket for the first time. Then for the second consecutive time in 2007, Anil Sharma became [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]]. In the year 2012, [[Khurja (Assembly constituency)|Khurja]] seat was secured. He contested on the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] ticket from [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur Assembly]] seat but lost to [[Samajwadi Party|SP]]'s [[Mukesh Sharma]]. In the year 2017, he was elected MLA from [[Shikarpur (Assembly constituency)|Shikarpur Assembly]] seat as a member of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref name=LH/>\n==Post helds==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! # !! From !! To !! Position !! Comments\n|-\n| 1 ||February 2002 || May 2007|| Member, [[14th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref name=\" 2002 Election Results  \">{{cite news|title= 2002 Election Results|publisher=[[Election Commission of India]] website|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_2002/Stat_rep_UP_2002.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2 ||May 2007 || March 2012 || Member, [[15th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref name=\" 2007 Election Results  \">{{cite news|title= 2007 Election Results|publisher=[[Election Commission of India]] website|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_2007/StatReport_AS_2007_UTTAR_PRADESH.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3 ||March 2017 || Incumbent || Member, [[17th Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eci.nic.in/eci_main/archiveofge2017/UP/10.Detailed%20Results.pdf|title=Uttar Pradesh 2017 Result|website=Election Commission of India|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4 ||August 2019 || Incumbent || Minister of State for Forest, Environment, Zoological Garden in [[Government of Uttar Pradesh]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|India|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Anil}}\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bulandashahar district]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:People from Bulandashahar districtusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anil_Sharma_(Uttar_Pradesh_politician)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Qatar", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Qatar}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 CodddD-19 Pandemic in Qatar\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Qatar]]\n| first_case      = [[Doha]]\n| arrival_date    = 27 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=27|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 131<ref name=\"MoPH\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 - (COVID-19) |url=https://www.moph.gov.qa/english/Pages/Coronavirus2019.aspx |website=Ministry of Public Health |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 4<ref name=\"MoPH\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1832<ref name=\"MoPH\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.moph.gov.qa/english/Pages/Coronavirus2019.aspx/ www.moph.gov.qa]\n}}\n\n\nThe first case of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] disease caused by the [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus in [[Qatar]] was confirmed on 27 February 2020, with cases mostly coming from [[Iran]]. As of 04 April,  Qatar is the 2nd country in the [[Arab World]] by number of confirmed cases at 1,604. The total recoveries stand at 123, with 4 deaths.<ref name=\"MoPH\" />\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Qatar medical cases chart}}\n===March 2020===\n\nOn March 9, 2020, Qatar announced a closure of all schools and universities until further notice<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/qatar-bans-travellers-14-countries-coronavirus-concerns-200309060851684.html| title = Qatar announces closure of schools, universities over coronavirus| date = March 9, 2020| access-date = March 9, 2020| language = en| trans-title = }}</ref> and placed a travel ban on 15 countries: [[Bangladesh]], [[China]], [[Egypt]], [[India]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]], [[Italy]], [[Lebanon]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], [[Philippines|the Philippines]], [[South Korea]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Syria]], and [[Thailand]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 11, 2020, the Qatari Ministry of Public Health (MOPH) announced the confirmation of 238 new cases of the disease in a single day, bringing the country's total to 262.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/qatar-coronavirus-cases-jump-238-day-200311154834214.html| title = Qatar's coronavirus cases jump by 238 in one day| date = March 11, 2020| access-date = March 11, 2020| language = en| trans-title = }}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2020, the Ministry of Public Health announced the confirmation of 58 new cases of the disease, bringing the total to 320. The same day, the [[CEO]] of [[Qatar Airways]], [[Akbar Al Baker]], stirred controversy by claiming that there was no scientific evidence proving that coronavirus can be transmitted during the incubation period.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://onemileatatime.com/qatar-airways-ceo-coronavirus/ | title=Qatar Airways CEO Causes Coronavirus Controversy| date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 2020, the Ministry of Public Health MOPH of Qatar, 17 new cases were confirmed by the Ministry of Public Health. Qatar expanded its travel ban to include three new countries: [[Germany]], [[Spain]] and [[France]]. On March 16, 2020, the Ministry of Public Health announced the recovery of four people from the disease at a press conference. Eight new coronavirus cases are reported, bringing the total to 460 on 19 March. Two of the new cases are Qataris who had been to Europe, while the others are migrant workers. Most of the reported cases are linked to migrant workers, although the government has not reported nationalities. Preparations for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] continue on schedule.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-hits-migrant-workers-qatar-133251577.html Coronavirus hits migrant workers in Qatar] Reuters, 19 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nTen new coronavirus cases were reported the next day on 20 March, bringing the total to 470.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/20/Qatar-reports-10-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-470.html|title=Qatar reports 10 new coronavirus cases, total at 470|date=2020-03-20|website=english.alarabiya.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> There were 11 new coronavirus cases reported on 21 March taking the total to 481.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/21/03/2020/11-new-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-Qatar-taking-total-to-481|title= 11 new coronavirus cases reported in Qatar taking total to 481|website=thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The Ministry of Municipal and Environment closed all parks and public beaches in order to curb the spread of coronavirus (Covid19).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/21/03/2020/Ministry-decides-to-end-camping-season-from-Sunday|title=Ministry decides to end camping season from Sunday|website=thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nMinistry of Public Health announced 13 new confirmed cases of Covid-19 as well as six further cases of people who have recovered from the virus, bringing the total cases of recovery to 33 cases on 22 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/22/03/2020/6-recover-as-13-more-report-positive-for-corona-in-Qatar|title= 6 recover as 13 more report positive for corona in Qatar|website=thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Ministry of Public Health (MoPH) seeking volunteers to support Qatar's response to the Covid-19 outbreak. A spokesperson for the Supreme Committee for Crisis Management, HE Lolwah Rashid AlKhater, said: \u201cWe are looking for volunteers to help Qatar\u2019s healthcare sector as the number of Covid-19 cases increases and creates a strain on resources. We need to stand together as a community and work to support Qatar\u2019s public and private sectors during these trying times.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/659061/Volunteers-urged-to-apply-as-quickly-as-possible-f|title= Volunteers urged to apply 'as quickly as possible' for MoPH campaign|website=www.gulf-times.com|date= 23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The same day, the Ministry of Commerce and Industry in a circular said it was decided to temporarily close all restaurants, cafes, food outlets, and food trucks in the following locations from March 23 until further notice: Sports clubs, [[Lusail Marina]], food trucks area, [[Doha Corniche]], [[Al Khor Corniche]], and [[Aspire Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/659072/Temporary-closure-of-eateries-starts-at-select-loc|title= Temporary closure of eateries starts at select locations|website=www.gulf-times.com|date= 23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry of Public Health announced today 7 new confirmed cases with four more people now recovered on the day. The new cases of infection are related to travellers who recently came to the State of Qatar and to expatriate workers, including two cases of Qatari citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moph.gov.qa/english/Pages/Coronavirus2019.aspx|title= The Ministry of Public Health announced today 7 new confirmed cases of coronavirus 2019 (Covid-19) were recorded in the State of Qatar with 4 more people now recovered.|website= www.moph.gov.qa|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Qatar's Health Ministry announced that 25 new coronavirus cases have been reported in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/qatar/coronavirus-qatar-reports-25-new-covid-19-cases-total-cases-reach-526-1.1585075949086|title= Coronavirus: Qatar reports 25 new Covid-19 cases, total cases reach 526|website=www.gulfnews.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, The Ministry of Public Health today announced the registration of 11 new confirmed cases of coronavirus 2019 (Covid-19) in the State of Qatar. Some of the new cases of infection are related to the travelers who came recently to the State of Qatar and others belong to people in contact with infected cases, including 5 cases of Qatari citizens. The newly infected cases are in isolation, and they are receiving medical care. The Ministry of Public Health continues to conduct checks for all citizens travelling from abroad, as well as all contacts of infected cases. The total number of people tested for COVID-19 by the Ministry of Public Health has now reached more than 12,000. The Ministry of Public Health urges all agencies and individuals to follow preventive measures and adhere to the requirements of home isolation to ensure their safety and that of their community, and not to go out unless absolutely necessary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moph.gov.qa/english/Pages/Coronavirus2019.aspx|title= The Ministry of Public Health today announced the registration of 11 new confirmed cases of coronavirus 2019 (Covid-19) in the State of Qatar|website=www.moph.gov.qa|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, Spokesperson of the Supreme Committee for Crisis Management [[H E Lolwah bint Rashid bin Mohammed Al Khater]] announced 12 new cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) in Qatar. Total recovery cases are now at 43, with two new cases. The Spokesperson stated the new cases are in complete isolation. The total number of COVID-19 tests done in Qatar now stands at 13681.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/26/03/2020/12-new-COVID-19-cases-in-Qatar,-total-now-549|title= 12 new COVID-19 cases in Qatar, total now 549|website=www.thepeninsulaqatar.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, The Ministry of Public Health reported the registration of 13 new confirmed cases of coronavirus 2019 (Covid-19) in the State of Qatar. The total number stands at 562. Some new cases are related to travellers who came to the State of Qatar and others to contacts. The new cases have been put into quarantine and are receiving the necessary medical care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/27/03/2020/13-new-Covid-19-cases,-total-562-in-Qatar|title= 13 new Covid-19 cases, total 562 in Qatar|website=www.thepeninsulaqatar.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Qatar reported its first death case from the novel coronavirus, in addition to 28 new infections, bringing the total of confirmed cases to 590, according to the Ministry of Public Health and two more recoveries, taking the tally to 45 cured patients. The ministry revealed that it has tested more than 16,582 people for Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-qatar-rises-to-634/1784399|title=Qatar reports first death from novel coronavirus, 28 new infections|last=|first=|date=|website=www.gulfnews.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, The Ministry of Public Health along with other new articles have stated that 44 more cases were confirmed for coronavirus (Covid-19) in the State of Qatar. Which brings the total number of cases to 634.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-qatar-rises-to-634/1784399|title=Number of coronavirus cases in Qatar rises to 634}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, The Ministry of Public Health announced the registration of 59 new confirmed cases of coronavirus (Covid 19), in addition to 3 more cases of patients recovered from the virus.\n\nOn March 31, The Ministry of Public Health announces 88 new confirmed cases of coronavirus (Covid-19) and 11 more patients having recovered.\n\n===April 2020===\nOn April 1, The Ministry of Public Health announced 54 new confirmed cases of coronavirus (Covid-19) and 9 more patients having recovered from the virus which brings the total cases of recovery in the State of Qatar to 71.\n\nOn April 2, The Ministry of Public Health announced the registration of 114 new confirmed cases of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) and the recovery of one patient in addition to the announcement of a third death due to COVID-19 in the State of Qatar.\n\nOn April 3, The Ministry of Public Health announced the registration of 126 new confirmed cases of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) and the recovery of 21 patients in the State of Qatar.\n\nOn April 4, The Ministry of Public Health announced the registration of 250 new confirmed cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) and stated that 16 more people have recovered from COVID-19, bringing the total number of people have recovered in the State of Qatar to 109.\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===Migrant workers in lockdown===\n[[Qatar]] \"labour camps\" are being locked down by authorities and workers with coronavirus concentrated inside them are in conditions that deny them basic [[human rights]]. According to a report at the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'', hundreds of construction workers now have the virus amid the global pandemic and Qatar's policies of concentrating the people  together in \"squalid, over-crowded camps\" enables the virus to \u201cspread  rapidly.\u201d<ref name=QatarPrison/>\n\n\"Inside the quarantined camps, workers describe an atmosphere of fear and uncertainty,\" the report notes. Workers are being put on unpaid leave and it is getting worse by the day. Labour camps where the coronavirus sufferers are concentrated are given numbers within Qatar's expansive gulag of workers camps. \"Workers from camp 1 to camp 32 are in lockdown,\" one man from Bangladesh said to the ''Guardian''.<ref name=QatarPrison>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/20/covid-19-lockdown-turns-qatars-largest-migrant-camp-into-virtual-prison|title=Covid-19 lockdown turns Qatar's largest migrant camp into 'virtual prison'|newspaper= The Guardian|date=20 March 2020|last1=Pattisson|first1=Pete|last2=Sedhai|first2=Roshan}}</ref>\n\nPolice guard the perimeter of a large one within the so-called \"Industrial Area\", where thousands of workers are confined, prohibiting anyone to enter or leave. The workers in question had been working on infrastructure for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=QatarPrison/> [[Doha]]'s Industrial Area as a whole is a large collection of warehouses, workers' quarters, and factories, located about a half an hour's drive from the capital. The hundreds of thousands of workers present live in rooms of eight to ten people.<ref name=QatarPrison/>\n\n===Public announcement of nationals who violated home quarantine===\nQatar state television named and shamed 14 nationals who violated restrictions set to curb the spread of the coronavirus, adding that nine of the persons had been arrested by authorities. The 14 individuals were said to have violated a home quarantine pledge they undertook after returning from abroad, a presenter on Qatar state TV said. Home isolation was an option given to nationals who returned to Qatar after the nation reported a spike in coronavirus cases.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-qatar-television-names-14-nationals-who-violated-movement-restrictions|title=Coronavirus: Qatar names and shames nationals who violated home quarantine|website= www.middleeasteye.net}}</ref>\n\n== Graph of Active Cases (as of April 7, 2020) ==\n\n=== Active Cases vs. Days since February 29, 2020 ===\n<graph>{\n\t\"version\": 2,\n\t\"width\": 750,\n\t\"height\": 300,\n\t\"data\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"name\": \"table\",\n\t\t\t\"values\": [\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 1,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 3\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 7\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 3,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 8\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 6,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 11\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 7,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 12\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 8,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 15\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 9,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 18\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 10,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 24\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 11,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 262\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 13,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 320\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 14,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 337\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 15,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 397\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 16,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 435\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 17,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 438\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 18,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 448\n\t\t\t\t},\n