{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Libya", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Libya}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Libya\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Libya]]\n| first_case      = [[Tripoli]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[China]] \n| recovery_cases  = 1\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 20<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live): 1,341,662 Cases and 74,522 Deaths from COVID-19 Virus Outbreak - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info |language=en |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThis article is about the spread of the [[coronavirus]] in [[Libya]], during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 epidemic]].\n\nLibya is considered especially vulnerable to the epidemic due to the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|ongoing Libyan Civil War]], which has led to a dire humanitarian situation<ref name=first/> and a destruction of the nation's health infrastructure.<ref name=RocketAttack>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/condemns-rocket-attack-tripoli-hospital-200407140610239.html UN condemns rocket attack on Tripoli hospital], Al Jazeera (April 7, 2020).</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\nPrior to the coronavirus pandemic, Libya's healthcare system was already on the verge of collapse, given the chaos that has prevailed in the country [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|since 2011]].<ref name=450Prisoners>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/libya-frees-450-prisoners-stem-spread-coronavirus-200330093545745.html Libya frees more than 450 prisoners to stem spread of coronavirus], Al Jazeera (March 30, 2020).</ref> Warring factions in the [[Libyan Civil War]] disregarded repeated entreaties from the [[United Nations]] for a ceasefire during the pandemic.<ref name=RocketAttack/><ref name=Humanitarian>[https://reliefweb.int/report/libya/statement-humanitarian-coordinator-libya-yacoub-el-hillo-following-today-s-attack-al Statement by the Humanitarian Coordinator for Libya, Yacoub El Hillo, following today's attack on Al Khadra General Hospital in Tripoli], United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (April 6, 2020).</ref>\n\nThe internationally recognized [[Government of National Accord]] (GNA), based in Tripoli, and the rival government under [[Khalifa Haftar]], based in eastern Libya, both took steps to control the spread of COVID-19, through the closure of schools, markets, and some businesses.<ref name=450Prisoners/> Haftar's forces have attempted to take Tripoli, the Libyan capital, in [[2019\u201320 Western Libya offensive|an offensive that began in April 2019]].<ref name=450Prisoners/> Hundreds have been killed, and thousands have been [[Internally displaced person|displaced]], in the fighting.<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\nOn 24 March, Libya confirmed its first [[COVID-19]] case,<ref name=first>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-libya-measures/libya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-amid-fear-over-readiness-idUSKBN21B2SF|title=Libya confirms first coronavirus case amid fear over readiness|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> a 73-year-old man who had returned to the country in early March from a trip to [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\nOn March 30, the GNA announced the release of 466 detainees in Tripoli, as part of an effort to stop the spread of the virus in prisons.<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 2 April, Libya confirmed its first COVID-19 death. It was an 85-year-old Algerian woman.\n\nOn April 5, [[Mahmoud Jibril]], age 68, who headed the interim [[National Transitional Council]] in 2011, died from COVID-19 in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], having been admitted to the hospital on March 21.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/libya-prime-minister-mahmoud-jibril-dies-coronavirus-200405162834328.html Former Libya Prime Minister Mahmoud Jibril dies from coronavirus], Al Jazeera (April 5, 2020).</ref>\n\nBy April 7, Libya had confirmed 20 cases of COVID-19, mostly in western Libya.<ref name=APTripoli/> \n\nOn April 6, Forces under the command of [[Khalifa Haftar]] launched a [[BM-21 Grad|Grad rocket]] attack<ref name=APTripoli>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/07/world/middleeast/ap-ml-libya-.html Eastern Libyan Forces Attack Tripoli Hospital for Second Day], Associated Press (April 7, 2020).</ref> against Al Khadra General Hospital, one of Tripoli's largest hospitals, injured six health workers and substantially damaged the hospital,<ref name=RocketAttack/> where 300 patients, including two COVID-19 patients, were being treated.<ref name=APTripoli/> This was the third time that Haftar's forces attacked medical facilities during their intensified siege of Tripoli.<ref name=APTripoli/> The [[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] condemned the attack as an \"appalling\" and \"clear violation of [[international humanitarian law]] ... It is unacceptable at a time when healthcare and health workers are vital in our fight against a global pandemic.\"<ref name=RocketAttack/> The office stated that \"This senseless escalation must stop so that health authorities and aid agencies can respond to COVID-19 and continue reaching people in need of urgent humanitarian assistance.\"<ref name=Humanitarian/> Renewed rocket attacks against the hospital continued the following day.<ref name=APTripoli/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Libyan Crisis (2011\u2013present)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Libya|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Libya]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Libya]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Libya]]\n[[Category:Libyan Crisis (2011\u2013present)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Libya}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Libya\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Libya]]\n| first_case      = [[Tripoli]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[China]] \n| recovery_cases  = 1\n| deaths          = 1\n| confirmed_cases = 20<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live): 1,341,662 Cases and 74,522 Deaths from COVID-19 Virus Outbreak - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info |language=en |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThis article is about the spread of the [[coronavirus]] in [[Libya]], during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 epidemic]].\n\nLibya is considered especially vulnerable to the epidemic due to the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|ongoing Libyan Civil War]], which has led to a dire humanitarian situation<ref name=first/> and a destruction of the nation's health infrastructure.<ref name=RocketAttack>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/condemns-rocket-attack-tripoli-hospital-200407140610239.html UN condemns rocket attack on Tripoli hospital], Al Jazeera (April 7, 2020).</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\nPrior to the coronavirus pandemic, Libya's healthcare system was already on the verge of collapse, given the chaos that has prevailed in the country [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|since 2011]].<ref name=450Prisoners>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/libya-frees-450-prisoners-stem-spread-coronavirus-200330093545745.html Libya frees more than 450 prisoners to stem spread of coronavirus], Al Jazeera (March 30, 2020).</ref> Warring factions in the [[Libyan Civil War]] disregarded repeated entreaties from the [[United Nations]] for a ceasefire during the pandemic.<ref name=RocketAttack/><ref name=Humanitarian>[https://reliefweb.int/report/libya/statement-humanitarian-coordinator-libya-yacoub-el-hillo-following-today-s-attack-al Statement by the Humanitarian Coordinator for Libya, Yacoub El Hillo, following today's attack on Al Khadra General Hospital in Tripoli], United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (April 6, 2020).</ref>\n\nThe internationally recognized [[Government of National Accord]] (GNA), based in Tripoli, and the rival government under [[Khalifa Haftar]], based in eastern Libya, both took steps to control the spread of COVID-19, through the closure of schools, markets, and some businesses.<ref name=450Prisoners/> Haftar's forces have attempted to take Tripoli, the Libyan capital, in an offensive that began in April 2019.<ref name=450Prisoners/> Hundreds have been killed, and thousands have been [[Internally displaced person|displaced]], in the fighting.<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\nOn 24 March, Libya confirmed its first [[COVID-19]] case,<ref name=first>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-libya-measures/libya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-amid-fear-over-readiness-idUSKBN21B2SF|title=Libya confirms first coronavirus case amid fear over readiness|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> a 73-year-old man who had returned to the country in early March from a trip to [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\nOn March 30, the GNA announced the release of 466 detainees in Tripoli, as part of an effort to stop the spread of the virus in prisons.<ref name=450Prisoners/>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 2 April, Libya confirmed its first COVID-19 death. It was an 85-year-old Algerian woman.\n\nOn April 5, [[Mahmoud Jibril]], age 68, who headed the interim [[National Transitional Council]] in 2011, died from COVID-19 in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], having been admitted to the hospital on March 21.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/libya-prime-minister-mahmoud-jibril-dies-coronavirus-200405162834328.html Former Libya Prime Minister Mahmoud Jibril dies from coronavirus], Al Jazeera (April 5, 2020).</ref>\n\nBy April 7, Libya had confirmed 20 cases of COVID-19, mostly in western Libya.<ref name=APTripoli/> \n\nOn April 6, Forces under the command of [[Khalifa Haftar]] launched a [[BM-21 Grad|Grad rocket]] attack<ref name=APTripoli>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/07/world/middleeast/ap-ml-libya-.html Eastern Libyan Forces Attack Tripoli Hospital for Second Day], Associated Press (April 7, 2020).</ref> against Al Khadra General Hospital, one of Tripoli's largest hospitals, injured six health workers and substantially damaged the hospital,<ref name=RocketAttack/> where 300 patients, including two COVID-19 patients, were being treated.<ref name=APTripoli/> This was the third time that Haftar's forces attacked medical facilities during their intensified siege of Tripoli.<ref name=APTripoli/> The [[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] condemned the attack as an \"appalling\" and \"clear violation of [[international humanitarian law]] ... It is unacceptable at a time when healthcare and health workers are vital in our fight against a global pandemic.\"<ref name=RocketAttack/> The office stated that \"This senseless escalation must stop so that health authorities and aid agencies can respond to COVID-19 and continue reaching people in need of urgent humanitarian assistance.\"<ref name=Humanitarian/> Renewed rocket attacks against the hospital continued the following day.<ref name=APTripoli/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Libyan Crisis (2011\u2013present)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Libya|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Libya]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Libya]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Libya]]\n[[Category:Libyan Crisis (2011\u2013present)]]\n", "name_user": "Neutrality", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarch 2020:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Libya"}
{"title_page": "PotPlayer", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = PotPlayer\n| logo                   = Daum_PotPlayer_logo.jpg\n| screenshot             = Pot player 1.7.18346.jpg\n| caption                = Screenshot of PotPlayer 1.7.18346\n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = Kang Yong-huee\n| developer              = [[Kakao]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = {{Latest stable software release/PotPlayer}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Windows 10]], [[Windows 8.1]], [[Windows 7]], [[Windows Vista]], [[Windows XP]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = 25.6MB (32bit)<br/>25.9MB (64bit)\n| language               = Arabic, Armenian, Azerbaijan, Belarusian, Bulgarian, Catalan, Chinese (Simplified and Traditional), Czech, English, French, German, Greek, Hebrew, Hong Kong, Hungarian, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Kurdish, Persian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Serbian, Spanish, Swedish, Tajik (Cyrillic), Thai, Turkish, Ukrainian, Uzbek (Latin)\n| genre                  = [[Media player (software)|Media player]]\n| license                = [[Freeware]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://potplayer.daum.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''PotPlayer''' is a [[Media player (software)|multimedia]] software player developed for the [[Microsoft Windows]] operating system by South Korean Internet company [[Kakao]] (formerly Daum Communications).\n\nThe player competes against other popular media players available for the Windows operating system such as [[VLC media player]], [[GOM Player]], [[KMPlayer]], [[SMPlayer]] and [[Media Player Classic]]. PotPlayer's reception has been positive{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} with reviewers complimenting the program's very high number of settings and customizations available<ref name=\"Lifehacker\">{{cite web|last1=Gordon|first1=Whitson|title=The Best Video Player for Windows|url=https://lifehacker.com/5822672/the-best-video-player-for-windows|website=Lifehacker|accessdate=April 28, 2016|date=July 19, 2011}}</ref> as well as its lightweight nature<ref name=\"Lifehacker\"/> and support for a large variety of formats.<ref name=\"SoftPedia\">{{cite web|last1=Dragomir|first1=Mircea|title=PotPlayer|url=https://www.softpedia.com/get/Multimedia/Video/Video-Players/PotPlayer.shtml|website=SoftPedia|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref> Among its criticisms, reviewers also noted that its high number of settings is \"one of its biggest weaknesses. It has a ton of different settings which unfortunately makes wading through the checkbox-laden settings menu kind of a pain\"<ref name=\"Lifehacker\"/> and that the options menu is \"confusing\".<ref name=\"Softonic\">{{cite web|last1=Park|first1=Chris|title=Powerful media player with support for lots of formats|url=https://potplayer.en.softonic.com/|website=Softonic|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPotPlayer contains many built-in keyboard shortcuts and hotkeys.[http://www.latestsolution.com/2016/07/top-and-best-keyboard-shortcut-daumpotplayer.html]\n\nAs of at least late 2019 PotPlayer began to be surreptitiously bundled with third-party spamware and dubious unwanted quasi-malware which often self-installed without permission, which has led to an exodus from PotPlayer's previously enthusiastic user community. \n\n==See also==\n* [[K-Multimedia Player]] (also by Kang Yong-Huee)\n* [[Comparison of video player software]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://potplayer.daum.net}}\n{{Daum Kakao}}\n\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n\n[[Category:Windows media players]]\n[[Category:Windows-only freeware]]\n[[Category:Media players]]\n[[Category:Kakao]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = PotPlayer\n| logo                   = Daum_PotPlayer_logo.jpg\n| screenshot             = Pot player 1.7.18346.jpg\n| caption                = Screenshot of PotPlayer 1.7.18346\n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = Kang Yong-huee\n| developer              = [[Kakao]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = {{Latest stable software release/PotPlayer}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Windows 10]], [[Windows 8.1]], [[Windows 7]], [[Windows Vista]], [[Windows XP]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = 25.6MB (32bit)<br/>25.9MB (64bit)\n| language               = Arabic, Armenian, Azerbaijan, Belarusian, Bulgarian, Catalan, Chinese (Simplified and Traditional), Czech, English, French, German, Greek, Hebrew, Hong Kong, Hungarian, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Kurdish, Persian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Serbian, Spanish, Swedish, Tajik (Cyrillic), Thai, Turkish, Ukrainian, Uzbek (Latin)\n| genre                  = [[Media player (software)|Media player]]\n| license                = [[Freeware]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://potplayer.daum.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''PotPlayer''' is a [[Media player (software)|multimedia]] software player developed for the [[Microsoft Windows]] operating system by South Korean Internet company [[Kakao]] (formerly Daum Communications).\n\nThe player competes against other popular media players available for the Windows operating system such as [[VLC media player]], [[GOM Player]], [[KMPlayer]], [[SMPlayer]] and [[Media Player Classic]]. PotPlayer's reception has been positive{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}} with reviewers complimenting the program's very high number of settings and customizations available<ref name=\"Lifehacker\">{{cite web|last1=Gordon|first1=Whitson|title=The Best Video Player for Windows|url=https://lifehacker.com/5822672/the-best-video-player-for-windows|website=Lifehacker|accessdate=April 28, 2016|date=July 19, 2011}}</ref> as well as its lightweight nature<ref name=\"Lifehacker\"/> and support for a large variety of formats.<ref name=\"SoftPedia\">{{cite web|last1=Dragomir|first1=Mircea|title=PotPlayer|url=https://www.softpedia.com/get/Multimedia/Video/Video-Players/PotPlayer.shtml|website=SoftPedia|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref> Among its criticisms, reviewers also noted that its high number of settings is \"one of its biggest weaknesses. It has a ton of different settings which unfortunately makes wading through the checkbox-laden settings menu kind of a pain\"<ref name=\"Lifehacker\"/> and that the options menu is \"confusing\".<ref name=\"Softonic\">{{cite web|last1=Park|first1=Chris|title=Powerful media player with support for lots of formats|url=https://potplayer.en.softonic.com/|website=Softonic|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPotPlayer contains many built-in keyboard shortcuts and hotkeys.[http://www.latestsolution.com/2016/07/top-and-best-keyboard-shortcut-daumpotplayer.html]\n\nAs of at least late 2019 PotPlayer began to be surrepticiously bundled with third-party spamware and dubious unwanted quasi-malware which often self-installed without permission, which has led to an exodus from PotPlayer's previously enthusiastic user community. \n\n==See also==\n* [[K-Multimedia Player]] (also by Kang Yong-Huee)\n* [[Comparison of video player software]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://potplayer.daum.net}}\n{{Daum Kakao}}\n\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n\n[[Category:Windows media players]]\n[[Category:Windows-only freeware]]\n[[Category:Media players]]\n[[Category:Kakao]]\n", "name_user": "Arnobpl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PotPlayer"}
{"title_page": "Anatol Arapu", "text_new": "{{short description|Moldovan economist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Expand Romanian|topic=gov|Anatol Arapu|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Anatol Arapu\n|image= Anatol Arapu (2015-07-10) 01.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption= Anatol Arapu in 2015\n|office        = [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister = [[Iurie Leanc\u0103]]<br/>[[Chiril Gaburici]]<br/>[[Valeriu Strele\u021b]]\n| president  = [[Nicolae Timofti]]\n|term_start  =14 August 2013\n|term_end= 20 January 2016\n|predecessor=[[Veaceslav Negru\u021ba]] \n|successor= [[Octavian Arma\u0219u]]\n|term_start2=22 May 1998\n|term_end2 =12 November 1999\n|predecessor2=[[Valeriu Chi\u021ban]]\n|successor2=[[Mihail Manoli]]\n|primeminister2= [[Ion Ciubuc]]<br/>[[Ion Sturza]]\n|primeminister3= \n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1962|11|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]], [[Ialoveni District]], [[Moldovan SSR]], USSR\n|occupation= [[Economist]]\n|alma_mater     = [[State University of Moldova]]\n|president2=[[Petru Lucinschi]]}}\n\n'''Anatol Arapu''' (born 27 November 1962 in [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]]) is a Moldovan [[economist]], who served as [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finances of Moldova]] from 14 August 2013 to January 2016, in three consecutive cabinets: [[Leanc\u0103 Cabinet]], [[Gaburici Cabinet]], and [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]]. He also was Minister of Finances in 1990s, in [[Ciubuc-2 Cabinet]] (22 May 1998 - 17 February 1999) and in [[Sturza Cabinet]] (12 March - 12 November 1999).<ref>[http://www.interese.md/ro/demnitar/arapu-anatolie?job=767 Arapu Anatolie \u2013 posturi de\u021binute]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAnatol Arapu was born on 27 November 1962 in the village of [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]], [[Ialoveni District|Ialoveni]]. He graduated from the Faculty of Economics of the [[State University of Moldova]] in 1985, the [[Moscow State University of Economics, Statistics, and Informatics|Economic and Statistical Institute of Moscow]] in 1987 and the Institute of the [[World Trade Organization]] in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]] in 1993.<ref>[http://unimedia.info/stiri/ministrul-finantelor--veaceslav-negruta--a-depus-cerere-de-demisie-64369.html Ministrul Finan\u021belor, Veaceslav Negru\u021ba, a depus cerere de demisie]. Accesat la 14 august 2013.</ref> In the period 1988-1992 he was director of the \"Moldova - EXIM\" trust. During 1994-1997 he worked as an assistant to the World Bank executive direction, and from 1997 to 1998 he was Ambassador of the Republic of Moldova to the [[European Union]], [[NATO]], [[Belgium]], the [[Netherlands]], and [[Luxembourg]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20130814104737/www.mf.gov.md/ro/newsitem/949 The President of the Republic of Moldova, Nicolae Timofti, signed on August 14, 2013, the Order for the appointment of Mr. Anatol Arapu as Minister of Finance]</ref>\n\nHe subsequently worked for [[Lukoil]] [[Rom\u00e2nia]] as a financial director for one year, and from 2001 to 2013 he served as Deputy General Manager for Economic and Financial Affairs.<ref>[http://www.publika.md/oficial-anatol-arapu-este-noul-ministru-al-finantelor-presedintele-nicolae-timofti-a-semnat-decretul-de-numire_1538031.html OFICIAL! Anatol Arapu este noul ministru al Finan\u021belor. Pre\u0219edintele Nicolae Timofti a semnat decretul de numire]. Accesat la 14 august 2013.</ref> From August 14, 2013, he is the [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finance of the Republic of Moldova]] initially in the [[Leanc\u0103 Cabinet]], then in the [[Gaburici Cabinet]] and the [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]]. Although he is not a party member, he has become Minister as being submitted by the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Moldova]].<ref>[http://pldm.md/who-we-are/conducerea/pldm-in-government PLDM \u00een Guvern]</ref><ref>[http://www.promis.md/persoane/anatol-arapu/ Anatol Arapu], promis.md</ref><ref>[http://unimedia.info/stiri/ce-spune-filat-despre-arapu-64409.html Ce spune Filat despre Arapu], unimedia.info</ref><ref>[http://ipn.md/ro/politica/56276 Vlad Filat: PLDM a promovat \u0219i va promova profesioni\u0219ti c\u0103rora nu le este indiferent\u0103 soarta \u021b\u0103rii]</ref>\n\nHe is married and has a child. He speaks [[Romanian language|Romanian]] (native), [[Russian language|Russian]] (fluent), [[English language|English]] (fluent) and [[French language|French]] (medium).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tribuna.md/2013/08/18/omul-saptaminii-anatol-arapu-ministrul-finantelor/ |title=Omul S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00eenii - Anatol Arapu, ministrul Finan\u021belor - Tribuna |access-date=2017-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064154/http://tribuna.md/2013/08/18/omul-saptaminii-anatol-arapu-ministrul-finantelor/ |archive-date=2016-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023745/http://www.gov.md/ro/content/anatol-arapu Anatol Arapu on gov.md (CV)] \n*[http://anticoruptie.md/stiri/cine-este-noul-ministru-al-finantelor-anatol-arapu/ Cine este noul ministru al Finan\u021belor, Anatol Arapu?]{{in lang|ro}}\n\n{{Strele\u021b Cabinet}}\n{{Gaburici Cabinet}}\n{{Leanc\u0103 Cabinet}}\n{{Alliance for European Integration}}\n\n{{Strele\u021b Cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arapu, Anatol}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moldovan economists]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to Belgium]]\n[[Category:People from Ialoveni District]]\n[[Category:Moldovan Ministers of Finance]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to the European Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Moldovan economist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Expand Romanian|topic=gov|Anatol Arapu|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox politician\n|name = Anatol Arapu\n|image= Anatol Arapu (2015-07-10) 01.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption= Anatol Arapu in 2015\n|office        = [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister = [[Iurie Leanc\u0103]]<br/>[[Chiril Gaburici]]<br/>[[Valeriu Strele\u021b]]\n| president  = [[Nicolae Timofti]]\n|term_start  =14 August 2013\n|term_end= 20 January 2016\n|predecessor=[[Veaceslav Negru\u021ba]] \n|successor= [[Octavian Arma\u0219u]]\n|term_start2=22 May 1998\n|term_end2 =12 November 1999\n|predecessor2=[[Valeriu Chi\u021ban]]\n|successor2=[[Mihail Manoli]]\n|primeminister2= [[Ion Ciubuc]]<br/>[[Ion Sturza]]\n|primeminister3= \n|birth_date={{bda|1962|11|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]], [[Ialoveni District]], [[Moldovan SSR]], USSR\n|occupation= [[Economist]]\n|alma_mater     = [[State University of Moldova]]\n|president2=[[Petru Lucinschi]]}}\n\n'''Anatol Arapu''' (born 27 November 1962 in [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]]) is a Moldovan [[economist]], who served as [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finances of Moldova]] from 14 August 2013 to January 2016, in three consecutive cabinets: [[Leanc\u0103 Cabinet]], [[Gaburici Cabinet]], and [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]]. He also was Minister of Finances in 1990s, in [[Ciubuc-2 Cabinet]] (22 May 1998 - 17 February 1999) and in [[Sturza Cabinet]] (12 March - 12 November 1999).<ref>[http://www.interese.md/ro/demnitar/arapu-anatolie?job=767 Arapu Anatolie \u2013 posturi de\u021binute]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAnatol Arapu was born on 27 November 1962 in the village of [[V\u0103sieni, Ialoveni|V\u0103sieni]], [[Ialoveni District|Ialoveni]]. He graduated from the Faculty of Economics of the [[State University of Moldova]] in 1985, the [[Moscow State University of Economics, Statistics, and Informatics|Economic and Statistical Institute of Moscow]] in 1987 and the Institute of the [[World Trade Organization]] in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]] in 1993.<ref>[http://unimedia.info/stiri/ministrul-finantelor--veaceslav-negruta--a-depus-cerere-de-demisie-64369.html Ministrul Finan\u021belor, Veaceslav Negru\u021ba, a depus cerere de demisie]. Accesat la 14 august 2013.</ref> In the period 1988-1992 he was director of the \"Moldova - EXIM\" trust. During 1994-1997 he worked as an assistant to the World Bank executive direction, and from 1997 to 1998 he was Ambassador of the Republic of Moldova to the [[European Union]], [[NATO]], [[Belgium]], the [[Netherlands]], and [[Luxembourg]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20130814104737/www.mf.gov.md/ro/newsitem/949 The President of the Republic of Moldova, Nicolae Timofti, signed on August 14, 2013, the Order for the appointment of Mr. Anatol Arapu as Minister of Finance]</ref> \n\nHe subsequently worked for [[Lukoil]] [[Rom\u00e2nia]] as a financial director for one year, and from 2001 to 2013 he served as Deputy General Manager for Economic and Financial Affairs.<ref>[http://www.publika.md/oficial-anatol-arapu-este-noul-ministru-al-finantelor-presedintele-nicolae-timofti-a-semnat-decretul-de-numire_1538031.html OFICIAL! Anatol Arapu este noul ministru al Finan\u021belor. Pre\u0219edintele Nicolae Timofti a semnat decretul de numire]. Accesat la 14 august 2013.</ref> From August 14, 2013, he is the [[Ministry of Finance (Moldova)|Minister of Finance of the Republic of Moldova]] initially in the [[Leanc\u0103 Cabinet]], then in the [[Gaburici Cabinet]] and the [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]]. Although he is not a party member, he has become Minister as being submitted by the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Moldova]].<ref>[http://pldm.md/who-we-are/conducerea/pldm-in-government PLDM \u00een Guvern]</ref><ref>[http://www.promis.md/persoane/anatol-arapu/ Anatol Arapu], promis.md</ref><ref>[http://unimedia.info/stiri/ce-spune-filat-despre-arapu-64409.html Ce spune Filat despre Arapu], unimedia.info</ref><ref>[http://ipn.md/ro/politica/56276 Vlad Filat: PLDM a promovat \u0219i va promova profesioni\u0219ti c\u0103rora nu le este indiferent\u0103 soarta \u021b\u0103rii]</ref>\n\nHe is married and has a child. He speaks [[Romanian language|Romanian]] (native), [[Russian language|Russian]] (fluent), [[English language|English]] (fluent) and [[French language|French]] (medium).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tribuna.md/2013/08/18/omul-saptaminii-anatol-arapu-ministrul-finantelor/ |title=Omul S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00eenii - Anatol Arapu, ministrul Finan\u021belor - Tribuna |access-date=2017-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064154/http://tribuna.md/2013/08/18/omul-saptaminii-anatol-arapu-ministrul-finantelor/ |archive-date=2016-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023745/http://www.gov.md/ro/content/anatol-arapu Anatol Arapu on gov.md (CV)] \n*[http://anticoruptie.md/stiri/cine-este-noul-ministru-al-finantelor-anatol-arapu/ Cine este noul ministru al Finan\u021belor, Anatol Arapu?]{{in lang|ro}}\n\n\n{{Strele\u021b Cabinet}}\n{{Gaburici Cabinet}}\n{{Leanc\u0103 Cabinet}}\n{{Alliance for European Integration}}\n\n{{Strele\u021b Cabinet}}{{DEFAULTSORT:Arapu, Anatol}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moldovan economists]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to  Belgium]]\n[[Category:People from Ialoveni District]]\n[[Category:Moldovan Ministers of Finance]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Moldova to the European Union]]\n\n\n{{Moldova-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatol_Arapu"}
{"title_page": "Al-Hiwar (magazine)", "text_new": "{{short description|Arabic magazine funded by the CIA}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Al-Hiwar''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0648\u0627\u0631}}) was an Arabic magazine published in [[Beirut]] between 1962 and 1967.<ref name=\"emh\"/><ref name=\"Mitchell2002\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Mitchell|title=Rule of Experts: Egypt, Techno-Politics, Modernity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z0JOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151|accessdate=9 March 2020|date=18 November 2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92825-1|page=151}}</ref> The magazine was established and financed by the [[CIA]] during the [[cultural Cold War]].<ref name=\"afm\">{{cite news|author1=Ursula Lindsey|title=Arab Magazines: A Neglected History Resurfaces|url=https://www.al-fanarmedia.org/2018/07/a-neglected-history-of-political-and-artistic-engagement/|accessdate=9 March 2020|work=Al Fanar Media|date=24 July 2018}}</ref> Generous funding was provided by the agency with the stipulation that it publish articles on the situation of [[Soviet Muslims]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Massad|first=Joseph|title=Islam in liberalism|publisher=University of Chicago Press|publication-place=Chicago London|year=2015|isbn=0-226-20622-X|oclc=871670666|page=83}}</ref> The magazine was originally designed as a publication to improve modern [[Arabic poetry]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Hanan Toukan |title=Whatever Happened to Iltiz\u0101m? Words in Arab Art after the Cold War|journal=Perspectivia |url=https://perspectivia.net/servlets/MCRFileNodeServlet/ploneimport_derivate_00011694/333-349_ohne_Abb.pdf |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe financial support of the magazine by the [[Congress for Cultural Freedom]] which was a cover organization by CIA was uncovered by ''[[the New York Times]]''<ref name=\"afm\"/> in April 1966.<ref name=\"emh\">{{cite journal|author=Elizabeth M. Holt|title=\u201cBread or Freedom\u201d: The Congress for Cultural Freedom, the CIA, and the Arabic Literary Journal \u1e24iw\u0101r (1962-67) |journal=Journal of Arabie Literature|date=2013|volume=44|pages=83-102 |url=https://hcommons.org/deposits/objects/hc:27212/datastreams/CONTENT/content |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> Following this, the magazine was closed.<ref name=\"afm\"/> The editor and founder of the magazine, Tawfiq Sayigh,<ref name=\"Mitchell2002\"/> left [[Lebanon]] as a result of this event.<ref name=\"afm\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:1967 disestablishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:CIA and Islamism]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Lebanese magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Beirut]]\n[[Category:Defunct literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Central Intelligence Agency front organizations]]\n\n\n\n{{lit-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Arabic magazine funded by the CIA}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Al-Hiwar''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0648\u0627\u0631}}) was an Arabic magazine published in [[Beirut]] between 1962 and 1967.<ref name=\"emh\"/><ref name=\"Mitchell2002\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Mitchell|title=Rule of Experts: Egypt, Techno-Politics, Modernity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z0JOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151|accessdate=9 March 2020|date=18 November 2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92825-1|page=151}}</ref> The magazine was established and financed by the [[CIA]] during the [[cultural Cold War]].<ref name=\"afm\">{{cite news|author1=Ursula Lindsey|title=Arab Magazines: A Neglected History Resurfaces|url=https://www.al-fanarmedia.org/2018/07/a-neglected-history-of-political-and-artistic-engagement/|accessdate=9 March 2020|work=Al Fanar Media|date=24 July 2018}}</ref> Generous funding was provided by the agency with the stipulation that it publish articles on the situation of [[Soviet Muslims]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Massad|first=Joseph|title=Islam in liberalism|publisher=University of Chicago Press|publication-place=Chicago London|year=2015|isbn=0-226-20622-X|oclc=871670666|page=83}}</ref> The magazine was originally designed as a publication to improve modern [[Arabic poetry]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Hanan Toukan |title=Whatever Happened to Iltiz\u0101m? Words in Arab Art after the Cold War|journal=Perspectivia |url=https://perspectivia.net/servlets/MCRFileNodeServlet/ploneimport_derivate_00011694/333-349_ohne_Abb.pdf |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe financial support of the magazine by the Congress for Cultural Freedom which was a cover organization by CIA was uncovered by ''[[the New York Times]]''<ref name=\"afm\"/> in April 1966.<ref name=\"emh\">{{cite journal|author=Elizabeth M. Holt|title=\u201cBread or Freedom\u201d: The Congress for Cultural Freedom, the CIA, and the Arabic Literary Journal \u1e24iw\u0101r (1962-67) |journal=Journal of Arabie Literature|date=2013|volume=44|pages=83-102 |url=https://hcommons.org/deposits/objects/hc:27212/datastreams/CONTENT/content |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> Following this, the magazine was closed.<ref name=\"afm\"/> The editor and founder of the magazine, Tawfiq Sayigh,<ref name=\"Mitchell2002\"/> left [[Lebanon]] as a result of this event.<ref name=\"afm\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:1967 disestablishments in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:CIA and Islamism]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Lebanese magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Beirut]]\n[[Category:Defunct literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Central Intelligence Agency front organizations]]\n\n\n\n{{lit-mag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Al-Andalusi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Hiwar_(magazine)"}
